Turn 64 (Student)
Yes—you can keep the tooltip in sync with the marker’s position by listening for the marker’s drag events and updating the tooltip’s content (or its position) each time the marker moves. In Leaflet, for example, you would do something like this:

```javascript
// Assume `marker` is a draggable marker with a bound tooltip
marker.on('drag', function(e) {
    const latLng = e.target.getLatLng();
    // Update the tooltip text (e.g., show the new coordinates)
    marker.setTooltipContent(`Lat: ${latLng.lat.toFixed(5)}, Lng: ${latLng.lng.toFixed(5)}`);
    // If you want the tooltip to follow the marker exactly, you can also
    // reposition it manually (Leaflet does this automatically for bound tooltips)
});
```

If you’re using the `dragend` event instead, the code runs only after the user releases the marker, which can be less “live” but may be sufficient for many use‑cases:

```javascript
marker.on('dragend', function(e) {
    const latLng = e.target.getLatLng();
    marker.setTooltipContent(`Lat: ${latLng.lat.toFixed(5)}, Lng: ${latLng.lng.toFixed(5)}`);
});
```

A few extra tips:

* **Make sure the tooltip is bound to the marker** (`marker.bindTooltip(...)`) so it moves with the marker automatically.
* **Set `permanent: true`** in the tooltip options if you want the tooltip to stay visible all the time, not just on hover.
* **Throttle updates** if you’re doing heavy calculations on each `drag` event; you can use `requestAnimationFrame` or a debounce function to avoid performance hiccups.

With these listeners in place, the tooltip will reflect the marker’s new location as soon as it’s dragged.

<<NEXT_STUDENT>>How can I change the tooltip’s style (font, background color, etc.) to match my map’s theme?<<END_NEXT_STUDENT>>

Turn 65 (Student)
You can style Leaflet tooltips (or any map library’s pop‑ups) with plain CSS. First give the tooltip a custom class when you create it:

```javascript
L.marker([lat, lng])
  .bindTooltip("My label", {
    className: "my-tooltip",   // custom class
    direction: "top"
  })
  .addTo(map);
```

Then write CSS rules for that class:

```css
.my-tooltip {
  font-family: "Helvetica Neue", Arial, sans-serif;  /* change font */
