Turn 71 (Student)
You can do either, but most developers keep them separate for readability. Nesting @media inside @supports works fine— the browser first checks the feature support, then applies the media query only if that support is present. This is handy when a new CSS feature should only be used on certain screen sizes (e.g., a grid layout that only makes sense on tablets).  

Conversely, nesting @supports inside @media means the media query is evaluated first; the feature test runs only on devices that match the media condition. This can reduce unnecessary feature checks on devices you don’t care about, but it also makes the CSS a bit harder to scan.  

In practice, many teams write them side‑by‑side:

```css
@supports (display: grid) {
  /* grid fallback for all browsers that support it */
}
@media (min-width: 768px) {
  /* layout tweaks for larger screens */
}
```

If you need a combination, a short nested block is fine, but keep the nesting shallow and comment why you chose that order. The cascade still follows normal specificity rules, so later rules will win if they have the same weight.

<<NEXT_STUDENT>>If I nest @media inside @supports, does the order change which styles apply when both conditions are true?<<END_NEXT_STUDENT>>

Turn 83 (Student)
Yes—you can wrap the overriding rule in a media query so it only fires on mobile devices. The rule inside the query still needs to be at least as specific as the original and must also use !important (or a higher‑specificity selector) to beat the original !important declaration. For example:

```css
/* Desktop rule */
.myClass {
    color: blue !important;
}

/* Mobile‑only override */
@media only screen and (max-width: 600px) {
    .myClass {
        color: red !important;   /* overrides the desktop blue on screens ≤600px */
    }
}
```

Because the media‑query block is evaluated after the desktop rule and the selector has the same specificity, the mobile rule wins on devices that match the query. If you need even higher specificity, you can add an extra class or element (e.g., `body .myClass`) inside the media query.

